/**
 * Migration 170: bulk backfill service_cities under-coverage (heatingoil-0nnk audit)
 *
 * Audit run via mcp__postgres-railway-readonly against all 314 active suppliers
 * with >=5 expected cities from their postal_codes_served (expanded via
 * zip-database.json). Found 201 suppliers with service_cities <90% of expected
 * city count — totaling 4,194 missing city entries.
 *
 * Root cause: migration authors historically hand-wrote a representative city
 * list rather than mechanically expanding the full ZIP footprint. Same defect
 * class as mig 168 / mig 169 fix (Shaffer Oil + S.J. Johnson).
 *
 * Fix is additive: service_cities = union(existing, expand(postal_codes_served)).
 * Existing city names are preserved verbatim (including supplier-published
 * aliases like Indian Head/Marbury/Chaptico that don't match zip-db's preferred
 * USPS name for the ZIP). Cannot shrink any supplier's coverage.
 *
 * Why service_cities matters:
 *   - supplierMatcher.js:106 Priority-2 city match (80 points). Under-populated
 *     lists silently degrade match score for users whose location resolves by
 *     city name (not ZIP).
 *   - generate-supplier-pages.js:273 — towns rendered on supplier profile page.
 *   - generate-bundled-suppliers.js — bundled iOS app supplier directory.
 *
 * Worst 3 expansions in this batch:
 *   fawcett-energy:    76 → 296 (+220)
 *   long-energy:       20 → 209 (+189)
 *   countryside-fuels:  3 → 187 (+184)
 *
 * Migration uses targeted UPDATE per supplier (not upsertSupplier) because
 * this is a single-field backfill — no need to round-trip the entire supplier
 * record. Always-UPDATE pattern: semantically idempotent since the precomputed
 * list is deterministic, and trying to detect no-ops via JSONB text comparison
 * is brittle.
 *
 * Data baked in below was computed from production DB snapshot 2026-05-16 +
 * zip-database.json (post mig 168/169 state, includes 15561/15564/15565/20610/
 * 20627/20635/20643/20661 hamlets). If postal_codes_served has drifted since
 * via ScrapeConfigSync union-merge, that's fine — the precomputed list is
 * still a strict expansion of what was authored at snapshot time, and is
 * union-applied at the cities level (no shrink possible).
 */

